    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-02-24T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-02-24T19:00:00-05:00" n="64"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d64">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15A5/682: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chairman of the American Delegation</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Davis</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-02-25T00:00:00+00:00"
                            >February 25, 1936—midnight</date>.<lb/>[Received February 25—7:10
                        p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>107. Your 44, February 25, 2 p.m. Sharing your preoccupation as to the anomalous
                    position in which we would be placed if we were to hang on in London for any
                    undue length of time waiting for a consummation of our labors until European
                    powers can adjust certain political questions, I have already indicated to the
                    Chairman of the Conference the difficulties which this might raise for us and
                    have endeavored to impress upon all of them the importance of reaching
                    conclusions without undue delay. Eden said he quite understood the situation and
                    was opposed to further dillydallying on the naval question.</p>
                <p>As indicated in my 105, February 25, 2 p.m. and my 106, February 25, 11 p.m., the
                    negotiations are reaching a stage where the Conference must soon come to a
                    head.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Davis</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
